Intuition
At every step, we need to select the two heaviest stones and smash them together.

Finding the maximum two elements repeatedly in an array would be inefficient because after every operation the array changes.

A max heap is the perfect data structure for this because it allows us to:

Retrieve the largest element in O(log n)
Remove the largest element in O(log n)
Insert a new stone in O(log n)

Since Python's heapq provides a min heap, we store the negative values of stones to simulate a max heap.

Approach
Convert every stone value into its negative and build a heap.
The smallest negative value represents the largest stone.
While there are at least two stones:
Remove the two largest stones from the heap.
If they are different:
Insert their difference back into the heap.
If they are equal:
Both stones are destroyed, so nothing is added.
After all operations:
If one stone remains, return its value.
Otherwise, return 0.

Complexity
Let n be the number of stones.

Building the heap: O(n)
Each smash operation performs at most:
Two removals
One insertion

Each heap operation takes O(log n) time.

Since each operation removes at least one stone, there are at most n operations.

Time Complexity: O(n log n)
Space Complexity: O(n)

Code
import heapq
class Solution:
    def lastStoneWeight(self, stones: List[int]) -> int:
        heap = [-stone for stone in stones]
        heapq.heapify(heap)
        while len(heap) > 1:
            stone1 = -heapq.heappop(heap)
            stone2 = -heapq.heappop(heap)
            if stone1 != stone2:
                heapq.heappush(heap, -(stone1-stone2))
        if len(heap) == 1:
            return -heap[-1]
        else:
            return 0
